      "span_text": "Biomarkers that predict primary tumours with metastatic potential are of clinical importance, as spread of tumour cells to the regional lymph nodes in the neck is the most important independent prognostic factor in head and neck cancer patients. The presence of lymph node metastases in HNSCC patients at the time of diagnosis reduces the survival to 50% compared with patients without nodal involvement (N0). In addition, nodal metastasis occurs in 20 -50% of patients with clinically N0 head and neck cancer. Treating the neck with either surgical neck dissection or radiotherapy is accompanied with significant side effects, and the treatment strategy of cervical lymph nodes is still under debate [CITATION_6] ."
